## JSM import runbook

When the orchestrator (or skillos) is ready to import these skills into
JSM management, the canonical motion is:

```bash
# 1. Verify the skills validate cleanly
jsm validate /Users/josh/.claude/skills/nango-integrations --json | jq -e '.success'
jsm validate /Users/josh/.claude/skills/railway-api --json | jq -e '.success'

# 2. Import via JSM (creates a pinned version)
jsm import nango-integrations --source /Users/josh/.claude/skills/nango-integrations
jsm import railway-api --source /Users/josh/.claude/skills/railway-api

# 3. Confirm in jsm list
jsm list 2>&1 | grep -E "nango-integrations|railway-api"
```

## Behavior parity note

The 19 affected scripts were 0755 (executable). Post-fix they are 0644
(read-only). Their shebang lines are preserved, so they can run via:

```bash
bash /Users/josh/.claude/skills/<skill>/scripts/<name>.sh [args...]
```

Documented consumers (skill SKILL.md) typically invoke them via the
`bash <path>` form already; direct `<path> args` invocation will fail
with "permission denied" until the consumer is updated. The skill's
SKILL.md should be checked for any `<path> args` invocations and
updated to `bash <path> args` form. (Out of scope for this dispatch;
surface as follow-up.)
